            `})}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:["That formula is the ",(0,rt.jsx)("em",{children:"conceptual"})," objective \u2014 what we want the policy to maximise. The thing PPO actually optimises with gradient descent is a per-token surrogate that needs one more ingredient:"," ","an ",(0,rt.jsx)("strong",{children:"advantage"}),' for every token in every sampled completion. The advantage answers "was the token'," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"a_t"})," at state ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"s_t"})," better or worse than we'd have expected from ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"s_t"}),' on average?" \u2014 and using it instead of the raw reward dramatically reduces gradient variance. To compute the expected part, PPO trains a small'," ",(0,rt.jsx)("strong",{children:"value network"})," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"V_\\psi(s_t)"})," alongside the policy:"]}),(0,rt.jsx)("div",{className:"viz-math-block",children:(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{block:!0,tex:String.raw`
