            `})}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:[(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"V_\\psi"})," is typically the same size and architecture as the policy with one extra scalar head \u2014 same input (a prompt plus tokens-so-far), same context to digest, so it needs roughly the policy's capacity to estimate value accurately. A smaller"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"V_\\psi"})," would give biased estimates of expected reward, which would bias the advantage"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\hat{A}_t"}),", which would erase the variance-reduction benefit we introduced ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"V_\\psi"})," ","for in the first place. In practice it's just initialised from a copy of the SFT or reward-model checkpoint \u2014 clone the transformer body, swap the head. It's trained by simple mean-squared regression \u2014 every batch of rollouts produces observed per-state returns that serve as ground-truth labels, so"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"V_\\psi"})," gets a supervised update alongside each policy update. So PPO ends up carrying ",(0,rt.jsx)("em",{children:"four"})," models around during training: the policy ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_\\theta"}),", a frozen reference ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_{\\mathrm{ref}}"})," for the KL term, the reward model ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"r_\\varphi"}),", and the value net ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"V_\\psi"}),". Worth noting which of these is actually costly: only ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_\\theta"})," and"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"V_\\psi"})," are trained, and a trained model needs not just its parameters in memory but also its gradients and its optimizer state (Adam stores two extra moments per parameter), so it eats roughly ",(0,rt.jsx)("strong",{children:"3\u20134\xd7 the memory of a frozen model of the same size"}),". Since ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"V_\\psi"})," matches the policy's parameter count, this makes it the single most expensive piece of the PPO setup \u2014 bigger than the reward model (usually a smaller checkpoint, frozen) and bigger than"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_{\\mathrm{ref}}"})," (frozen, forward-pass only). The KL coefficient ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\beta"})," remains the dial we care about \u2014 it's the only one with a clean geometric interpretation, and it's the one the slider below controls."]}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:['The KL term is the geometric heart of the method. Without it, PPO will happily find responses the reward model loves but no human would \u2014 gushing token streams full of "great," "excellent," and five-star ratings, because those happened to correlate with high labels in the RM\'s training set. ',(0,rt.jsx)("em",{children:"Reward hacking."})," The KL penalty pulls the policy back toward the SFT distribution; the coefficient ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\beta"})," is the dial controlling how far it's allowed to wander."]}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:["Drag the slider below. Watch reward (blue) climb as"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\beta"})," drops \u2014 that's the policy chasing the RM. Then watch KL (red, dashed) explode, and the ",(0,rt.jsx)("em",{children:"true"})," response quality (green, an oracle we don't actually have in practice) peak and crash. The right-hand panel shows what the policy is actually generating at the current ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\beta"}),"."]}),(0,rt.jsx)(Pl,{}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:['The picture is the whole story of why RLHF is hard. The reward model is a learned proxy; pushing too hard against it will find places where the proxy disagrees with what we actually wanted. There is a "sweet spot" band where the policy uses the reward signal to genuinely improve over SFT, and where the KL penalty keeps it within distance of natural language. ',(0,rt.jsx)("em",{children:"Production deployments live in that band."})," Choosing the band is partly tuning ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\beta"}),", partly stopping training early, partly mixing PPO updates with continued SFT data so the policy can't forget how to talk."]}),(0,rt.jsx)("h3",{children:"The clipped surrogate, unpacked"}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:["The objective ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"J(\\pi_\\theta)"})," above is the conceptual goal \u2014 what we want to maximise. The actual loss PPO minimises with gradient descent looks fiddlier, for two reasons that come down to the same thing:"," ",(0,rt.jsx)("strong",{children:"rollouts are expensive, gradient steps are cheap"}),". Sampling a batch of completions from a 70B-parameter policy takes minutes of GPU time; one gradient step takes milliseconds. So PPO has a two-tier loop: an outer loop that samples a batch of rollouts, and an inner loop that does several (typically 4) gradient steps on that same batch before re-sampling."]}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:["That inner loop creates a small problem. At gradient step 1 of a fresh batch, the policy ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_\\theta"})," is identical to the snapshot ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_{\\theta_{\\mathrm{old}}}"})," we took before sampling. By gradient step 4, they've drifted apart \u2014 the samples were generated by the snapshot, but the gradient we're about to compute is for the updated policy. The samples are slightly stale."]}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:["The fix is"," ",(0,rt.jsx)("strong",{children:"importance sampling"}),": an expectation under"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_\\theta"})," equals an expectation under"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_{\\theta_{\\mathrm{old}}}"})," if we reweight each sample by the probability ratio between the two policies. Call that ratio ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\rho_t"}),":"]}),(0,rt.jsx)("div",{className:"viz-math-block",children:(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{block:!0,tex:String.raw`
