            `})}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:['Read it as: "how much more (or less) likely does the'," ",(0,rt.jsx)("em",{children:"current"}),' policy assign to this token than the snapshot policy that generated it?" At inner-loop step 1, ',(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\rho_t = 1"})," ","for every token and nothing changes. By step 4, ratios have drifted to perhaps 0.9 or 1.1 on typical tokens, and the loss weights each token's gradient accordingly. (The outer loop then refreshes ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_{\\theta_{\\mathrm{old}}} \\leftarrow \\pi_\\theta"})," ","and we sample again.) Note the three distinct policies now in play: ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_{\\mathrm{ref}}"})," (frozen SFT, never changes \u2014 the leash for the KL term),"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_{\\theta_{\\mathrm{old}}}"})," (snapshot at the start of this inner loop, refreshed each outer iteration), and"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\pi_\\theta"})," (the policy being optimised this gradient step)."]}),(0,rt.jsxs)("p",{children:["Importance sampling has a catch: the correction is only trustworthy when the two policies are close. Once"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\rho_t"})," wanders far from 1, we're putting heavy weight on samples that don't reflect what the current policy would actually generate. The "," ",(0,rt.jsx)("strong",{children:"clipped surrogate"})," ","is PPO's solution \u2014 it bounds how much a single token can pull the loss when its ratio has drifted past a trust band of width"," ",(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{tex:"\\varepsilon"})," (typically 0.2):"]}),(0,rt.jsx)("div",{className:"viz-math-block",children:(0,rt.jsx)(Nl,{block:!0,tex:String.raw`
